720770f-a.text:
Lafayette Street (Elm Street), north from Prince Street, showing the street under construction after the demolition of buildings which formerly stood there. The construction of the street necessitated the razing of many buildings in a northerly direction from Elm Street which terminated slightly south of Jersey Street, to Lafayette Place which commenced at Great Jones Street. The new street was named Lafayette Street several years later.
October 4, 1900.
Board of Transportation Photograph.
william B. Parsons Collection.

722662f-a.text:
(1)
63 to 67 Prince Street, north side, west from Lafayette (Elm) to Crosby Streets, showing at the N.W. corner of Lafayette Street, No. 63 Prince Street, the house where President Monroe died in 1831. About July 1926 it was moved to No. 95 Crosby Street, a point on the east side of the street and south of Prince Street. During same,it
became damaged and was gone in May 1928.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
(2)
A close-up of the entmances to Nos. 63 and 65.
1923.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
(3)
A view showing Lafayette Street in the foreground. Shown on the left are the sides and rears of No. 62, a 1-story shack at the corner (S.W.) and No. 64 a 4-story building. Across the background appear the upper portions of lofts on Crosby Street, north of Prince Street.
Date---T
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
